content: Well..., it's cool

Worth the price for what features it has. I always backup my device media content and certain data in case of failure to restore to another device, despite having the setting selected for restoring apps to different device in settings, sometimes there can be a glitch, especially if the device you purchased and installed apps from crashes, in the case of my LG-G2. I know there's people who think because it's Google, your Google account is fool proof, in respect of Google being on top of their game so to speak, there's no  100% sure way of complete protection from some unexpected issue arise during backup or restoring of one's device despite how reputable a company is, this is solely my opinion and my opinion only but speaking from experience nevertheless. I used a loaner phone, Samsung Galaxy J7, before purchasing my current device, LG V30. It seems that switching to the J7 I lost everything I had stored on Vid Trim Pro from the LG-G2, however, interestingly upon restoring from J7 to LG V30, seems to have restored some but NOT ALL of my edits. I don't blame this app for this happening, as stated above, I know things can happen outside of anyone's control and this is why I choose to backup anything and everything there is, including unfinished edits, alot easier to reload video to start as a new edit than not have a video at all. In short, I've used this app across multiple devices without any problem within the app itself, does what it says in app discription and for the price one certainly shouldn't be disappointed. Sometimes apps fail not bc due to developer error but device issues should also be considered, this is why I always be sure to include in my reviews the device(s) used. Vid Trim Pro- 5 STARS!

My Droid Maxx captures all videos at 10MP resolution, so one-minute is about a 120Mb sized file. Way too large to email, even using Dropbox. I needed to email a file of my coughing dog to our vet, so downloaded "VidTrim Pro" -- it only took a couple of clicks to resample this video file down to 480p & medium quality, which made about a 6MB sized MP4 file that I could easily email.  The final reduced quality was plenty good for the vet to diagnose a problem. I would have paid much more than $2.49 for this App. It was very simple to use, totally intuitive. And this is only one feature of the App. I haven't had time to see what else it does. But for $2.49 I saved a trip over to the vet with the dog.  I couldn't be happier. Makes me wonder why Motorola hasn't included this "transcoding" capability in its phone.
